<TITLE> Robben inspires Dutch to 3-0 win over Scotland </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 AMSTERDAM, March 29 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Headed goals from Klaas Jan Huntelaar and Robin van Persie in the first half set Netherlands on their way to a comfortable 3-0 win over Scotland in their World Cup Group Nine qualifier on Saturday. The Dutch made a hesitant start against the injury-depleted Scots but, inspired by winger Arjen Robben, opened the scoring through Huntelaar who headed home a fine cross from Mark van Bommel. On the stroke of halftime, Van Persie doubled the lead when he headed in Robben's corner and 13 minutes from time Dirk Kuyt converted a penalty after Christophe Berra fouled Huntelaar. "We missed pace in our game in the beginning but we also made the wrong choice too often by choosing the right flank instead of setting up Robben on the left like we planned," coach Bert van Marwijk said. "Finally the result is ok but our performance was so so," he added. The visitors, who had a goal disallowed midway through the second half, created their best chance after 12 minutes when Darren Fletcher linked up with Kenny Miller but Joris Mathijsen intervened. "We played against one of the top six countries in the world, so you can lose, but it still is not clear why the ref cancelled our goal that should have brought us back in the match," Scotland coach George Burley told reporters. Netherlands lead the group with 12 points from four matches, eight ahead of Iceland and Scotland. The Dutch are at home to Macedonia on Wednesday when the Scots host Iceland
